class Solution {
public:
    void helper(int idx, vector<int>& nums, vector<int>& ds, vector<vector<int>>& res) {
        res.push_back(ds); // add current subset at every step

        for (int i = idx; i < nums.size(); i++) {
            if (i > idx && nums[i] == nums[i-1]) continue; // skip duplicates
            ds.push_back(nums[i]);
            helper(i+1, nums, ds, res);
            ds.pop_back();
        }
    }
        vector<vector<int>> subsetsWithDup(vector<int>& nums) 
    {
        vector<vector<int>> res;
        vector<int> ds;

        //sort to handle duplicates
        sort(nums.begin(),nums.end()); //o(nlogn)

        helper(0,nums,ds,res);

        return res;
        
    }
};

Subsets II – Backtracking Approach (Handle Duplicates)
Sort nums to bring duplicates together.
Maintain temporary list ds and result res.
Call recursive helper(idx, nums, ds, res) starting from idx = 0.
In helper:
Push current ds to res at every step
Loop from i = idx to nums.size() - 1:
If i > idx && nums[i] == nums[i-1] → skip (avoid duplicate subsets)
Push nums[i] to ds → recurse helper(i+1) → pop (backtrack)

Time: O(2^N × N) → generate all subsets × copying each subset
Space: O(N) → recursion stack + temporary list

One-liner: “Sort + include/exclude recursion with skip for duplicates → all unique subsets generated.”
